01:04:59,186 --> 01:05:02,269
We shouldn't have
stopped marching
until we reached Moscow.

702
01:05:05,019 --> 01:05:06,644
They're from Switzerland.

703
01:05:06,686 --> 01:05:09,811
I had them sent
with the pouch to Berlin.

704
01:05:10,436 --> 01:05:12,103
They're a weakness of mine.

705
01:05:12,186 --> 01:05:15,811
When I was a child, my mother
would always reward me
with a chocolate.

706
01:05:18,103 --> 01:05:19,644
It's a dreadful habit.

707
01:05:20,187 --> 01:05:21,770
Chocolates
or seeking approval?

708
01:05:23,437 --> 01:05:24,686
Both.

709
01:05:26,978 --> 01:05:30,020
He was an officer
in the Abwehr,
German Military Intelligence.

710
01:05:33,353 --> 01:05:37,353
He says he knows the location
of certain Nazi V-2
rocket scientists in hiding.

711
01:05:37,479 --> 01:05:39,353
Ask him
where he wants to go.

712
01:05:43,104 --> 01:05:45,771
He wants to go to Chicago.
He has relatives there.

713
01:05:45,812 --> 01:05:49,271
Tell him if he provides us
with the names and locations
of the scientists,

714
01:05:49,354 --> 01:05:51,771
I'll arrange
an exit visa for him.

715
01:05:52,146 --> 01:05:55,605
As soon as he's
served his purpose, turn him
over to the Nazi catchers.

716
01:06:06,105 --> 01:06:10,605
An ex-Waffen-SS Group
Commander would like to speak
with you about asylum.

717
01:06:15,439 --> 01:06:16,980
It's very ugly, isn't it?

718
01:06:17,272 --> 01:06:19,272
It isn't meant to be jewelry.

719
01:06:20,938 --> 01:06:23,356
I lost the sound
in one ear altogether.

720
01:06:23,773 --> 01:06:27,356
I can hear with the help
of the apparatus
out of this ear,

721
01:06:27,481 --> 01:06:28,647
but they say
in one year or so...

722
01:06:28,773 --> 01:06:30,481
You hardly notice it's there.

723
01:06:37,606 --> 01:06:40,981
The Russians
are interested in making
a prisoner swap.

724
01:07:06,024 --> 01:07:10,774
We are prepared to offer you
some Jewish scientists
liberated in the East

725
01:07:10,815 --> 01:07:13,815
for some Nazi scientists
you have here in Berlin.

726
01:07:22,733 --> 01:07:25,025
These are the names
we're willing to discuss.

727
01:08:00,443 --> 01:08:04,276
I understand your cryptonym
for me is Ulysses.

728
01:08:05,276 --> 01:08:08,693
Is that for
the James Joyce book
or the Greek myth?

729
01:08:14,944 --> 01:08:17,652
Do you know
what our code name is for you?

730
01:08:21,902 --> 01:08:23,319
Mother.

731
01:08:27,027 --> 01:08:31,236
I took the first
hot bath yesterday
I've taken in three years,

732
01:08:31,277 --> 01:08:33,944
since the siege of Stalingrad.

733
01:08:35,653 --> 01:08:37,653
I sat for hours,

734
01:08:38,611 --> 01:08:40,486
looking out the window,

735
01:08:41,444 --> 01:08:43,111
soaking.

736
01:08:56,195 --> 01:08:59,695
When I was a soldier,
my fingers were frostbitten.

737
01:09:01,028 --> 01:09:03,445
Since then,
when I get cold,

738
01:09:04,362 --> 01:09:05,946
there is a pain.

739
01:09:08,987 --> 01:09:11,445
Maybe you shouldn't live
in Russia.

740
01:09:13,487 --> 01:09:15,612
We all have our weaknesses.

741
01:09:17,654 --> 01:09:19,029
What is yours?

742
01:09:22,321 --> 01:09:24,655
I had heard you were silent.

743
01:09:25,946 --> 01:09:28,112
"Made of stone," they said.

744
01:09:29,279 --> 01:09:34,154
What is the expression?
"The silence is deafening."

745
01:09:38,279 --> 01:09:42,696
You are going to be
a formidable adversary,
Mother.

746
01:09:52,364 --> 01:09:54,822
I look forward
to our association.

747
01:09:56,864 --> 01:09:59,280
I hope it lasts
for a long time.

748
01:10:15,448 --> 01:10:16,532
<i>I love you.</i>

749
01:10:17,948 --> 01:10:20,864
<i>People who really love
each other don't have secrets.</i>

750
01:10:21,782 --> 01:10:23,532
<i>You are safe here with me.</i>

751
01:10:23,657 --> 01:10:25,782
We were able
to make out the brand
of the fan.

752
01:10:25,865 --> 01:10:28,740
It's called a Froid.
It's Belgian.

753
01:10:28,782 --> 01:10:33,365
The object on the nightstand,
we're still trying to find out
what this is.

754
01:10:34,698 --> 01:10:36,490
We just can't get
any more definition out of it.

755
01:10:42,324 --> 01:10:43,990
<i>Who is this?</i>

756
01:10:45,324 --> 01:10:46,990
Who's this?

757
01:10:48,032 --> 01:10:51,074
<i>Hello, Father.
You have a birthday
coming up.</i>

758
01:10:51,366 --> 01:10:52,783
<i>I'm going to be five soon.</i>

759
01:10:54,157 --> 01:10:55,699
You're a big boy.

760
01:10:56,825 --> 01:10:59,366
<i>I'm bigger than Andrew,
and he's six.</i>

761
01:11:03,533 --> 01:11:06,658
<i>Is your mother there?
What? I can't hear you.</i>

762
01:11:09,158 --> 01:11:11,033
Is your mother there?

763
01:11:11,492 --> 01:11:13,866
<i>She's getting dressed
to go out with her friend.</i>

764
01:11:13,950 --> 01:11:16,492
<i>He has a new car.
He let me drive with him.</i>

765
01:11:19,450 --> 01:11:21,283
<i>Hello, Mr. Wilson.
This is Edna.</i>

766
01:11:21,659 --> 01:11:24,450
<i>Mrs. Wilson is upstairs.
She's getting ready
for dinner.</i>

767
01:11:24,492 --> 01:11:26,450
<i>I'll tell her
you're on the phone.</i>

768
01:11:28,826 --> 01:11:30,368
I'll call back.

769
01:11:37,951 --> 01:11:39,159
Pardon me.

770
01:11:40,660 --> 01:11:43,827
Do you need me
for anything else?
No, thank you.

771
01:11:52,910 --> 01:11:54,618
Do you ever eat, Mr. Carlson?

772
01:11:55,702 --> 01:11:59,160
I like to cook. Would you like
a home-cooked meal?

773
01:12:07,868 --> 01:12:11,077
<i>Have you ever read Ovid?
Metamorphoses
in the original Latin?</i>

774
01:12:12,452 --> 01:12:13,869
It's quite beautiful.

775
01:12:17,536 --> 01:12:21,036
"I grabbed a pile of dust
and, holding it up,

776
01:12:21,536 --> 01:12:25,370
"foolishly asked for
as many birthdays
as the grains of dust.

777
01:12:25,786 --> 01:12:28,703
"I forgot to ask that
they be years of youth."

778
01:12:30,036 --> 01:12:31,370
Bravo.

779
01:12:45,037 --> 01:12:46,662
I should be going.

780
01:12:54,787 --> 01:12:56,287
Would you like to stay?

781
01:12:59,579 --> 01:13:01,288
Would you like me to?

782
01:13:02,788 --> 01:13:04,997
I would like you to
very much.

783
01:13:14,371 --> 01:13:16,913
Maybe we could go
somewhere together?

784
01:13:17,038 --> 01:13:19,122
The lakes in Bavaria
are still beautiful.

785
01:13:20,539 --> 01:13:24,788
There was an inn there before
the war where they served
breakfast in bed all day.

786
01:13:49,206 --> 01:13:50,415
Hanna?

787
01:13:53,790 --> 01:13:55,665
I hope
you never go home.

788
01:13:58,039 --> 01:14:00,540
Bavaria is really
a beautiful place.

789
01:14:02,206 --> 01:14:06,249
I was born there.
My grandmother lived there.

790
01:14:07,540 --> 01:14:09,291
I really miss her.

791
01:14:10,999 --> 01:14:12,623
Why don't we go?

792
01:14:27,916 --> 01:14:30,208
I let a stranger
into our house.

793
01:15:40,377 --> 01:15:43,752
Mother! Father's here! Mother!

794
01:15:50,878 --> 01:15:52,211
Hello, Edward.

795
01:15:53,878 --> 01:15:55,420
Hello, Clover.

796
01:15:58,545 --> 01:15:59,587
I...

797
01:16:01,878 --> 01:16:04,378
I like to be called
Margaret now.

798
01:16:07,712 --> 01:16:09,795
It's very nice to see you.

799
01:16:11,462 --> 01:16:13,128
It's good to see you, too.

800
01:16:16,503 --> 01:16:18,336
I made something for you.

801
01:16:22,503 --> 01:16:24,795
See? It's a ship.

802
01:16:26,379 --> 01:16:29,212
But it's got
the flag of England.

803
01:16:31,379 --> 01:16:34,004
And then I put
a pirate flag there.

804
01:16:34,588 --> 01:16:36,796
And if you like,
you can count

805
01:16:37,463 --> 01:16:39,421
how many sails there are.

806
01:16:40,212 --> 01:16:42,046
You want to try that?

807
01:16:47,463 --> 01:16:48,588
Fifteen.

808
01:16:48,880 --> 01:16:50,255
That's right.

809
01:16:50,880 --> 01:16:52,297
Fifteen.

810
01:16:53,671 --> 01:16:56,297
No, no, it's yours.
I made it for you.

811
01:17:11,797 --> 01:17:13,839
If it's all right with you,

812
01:17:14,339 --> 01:17:16,881
I thought maybe we could sleep
in separate beds for a while,

813
01:17:16,922 --> 01:17:19,381
just until we get
to know each other again.

814
01:17:20,839 --> 01:17:22,715
I made up the spare room.

815
01:17:23,881 --> 01:17:25,214
All right.

816
01:17:33,882 --> 01:17:36,631
What do you hear
from your brother John?

817
01:17:39,715 --> 01:17:43,132
I thought you knew.
He was killed in Burma,
in 1944.

818
01:17:45,257 --> 01:17:48,340
You never mentioned it
in any of your letters.

819
01:17:50,840 --> 01:17:52,965
There wasn't very much to say.

820
01:18:01,050 --> 01:18:03,133
Six years is a long time.

821
01:18:06,924 --> 01:18:10,133
I was lonely
and I was with a man once.

822
01:18:13,799 --> 01:18:15,508
He wasn't very interesting.

823
01:18:19,592 --> 01:18:21,133
Were you with anyone?

824
01:18:23,967 --> 01:18:25,842
It was a mistake.

825
01:18:42,301 --> 01:18:45,176
Thank you for the ship
you made for me.

826
01:18:48,551 --> 01:18:49,843
You're welcome.

827
01:18:50,843 --> 01:18:52,509
I'm glad you like it.

828
01:18:54,593 --> 01:18:56,968
Mother said
you were in the war.

829
01:18:56,968 --> 01:18:59,968
Did you fight?
Did you kill anybody?

830
01:19:03,801 --> 01:19:05,135
No.

831
01:19:08,801 --> 01:19:11,260
Good night.
Good night.

832
01:19:29,428 --> 01:19:31,219
No! You're it!

833
01:19:31,802 --> 01:19:34,595
Hello, Father.
Hello, Edward. Hello.

834
01:19:34,886 --> 01:19:35,969
Hello, dear.

835
01:19:36,094 --> 01:19:37,553
There's somebody waiting
for you in the den.

836
01:19:40,637 --> 01:19:41,845
General.

837
01:19:43,803 --> 01:19:45,136
Edward.

838
01:19:46,803 --> 01:19:50,179
I'm sorry to barge in on you
like this. Your wife kindly
helped me to a drink.

839
01:19:52,220 --> 01:19:55,221
My feet,
they keep cutting off
pieces of them.

840
01:19:55,304 --> 01:19:58,137
It's not dignified for men
to have to die
from the feet up.

841
01:20:04,721 --> 01:20:07,512
Well, while everybody's been
feeling good about themselves,

842
01:20:07,763 --> 01:20:11,471
the Soviets,
without firing a shot, have
taken over half the world.

843
01:20:11,471 --> 01:20:13,138
They're breathing
down our necks.

844
01:20:13,179 --> 01:20:15,262
They'll be in our backyard
before you know it.

845
01:20:15,429 --> 01:20:16,679
So, I've been telling
the President

846
01:20:16,721 --> 01:20:19,138
about the need to create
a new
Foreign Intelligence Service.

847
01:20:19,180 --> 01:20:21,804
One that would do in peacetime
what OSS did during the war.

848
01:20:23,304 --> 01:20:26,471
Phillip Allen will be heading
the agency. Richard Hayes
will be his exec.

849
01:20:26,513 --> 01:20:28,054
And you'll be taking
Division C,

850
01:20:28,137 --> 01:20:30,805
special operations that report
only to the Director.

851
01:20:31,221 --> 01:20:33,554
It would be limited
to overseas, obviously.

852
01:20:33,638 --> 01:20:37,388
Subversive operations,
intelligence gathering
and analysis.

853
01:20:37,554 --> 01:20:40,805
And I'd be interested
in your thoughts about this.

854
01:20:41,388 --> 01:20:44,888
Particularly in your area
of expertise,
counterintelligence.

855
01:20:44,972 --> 01:20:47,471
I'd be glad to help
in any way I can.

856
01:20:47,554 --> 01:20:48,638
That's all right.

857
01:20:48,721 --> 01:20:50,721
Edward, go outside.

858
01:20:52,514 --> 01:20:54,555
Excuse me, sir. Margaret!

859
01:20:56,639 --> 01:20:58,305
Come on, Edward.

860
01:20:58,472 --> 01:21:00,972
Come. Let's go outside,
all right? Daddy's busy.

861
01:21:03,973 --> 01:21:05,305
Thank you.

862
01:21:14,223 --> 01:21:18,223
I have to tell you,
I have some real problems
with this whole thing,

863
01:21:18,306 --> 01:21:20,223
despite how much we need it.

864
01:21:21,139 --> 01:21:24,889
I'm concerned that
too much power will end up
in the hands of too few.

865
01:21:24,973 --> 01:21:28,640
It's always in somebody's
best interest to promote
enemies, real or imagined.

866
01:21:28,723 --> 01:21:33,807
I see this as America's eyes
and ears. I don't want it to
become its heart and soul.

867
01:21:35,473 --> 01:21:37,307
So I told the President,
for this to work,

868
01:21:37,390 --> 01:21:40,140
there's gonna have to be
some kind of civilian
oversight.

869
01:21:40,432 --> 01:21:41,890
Oversight?

870
01:21:42,640 --> 01:21:44,474
How can you have
a covert organization

871
01:21:44,599 --> 01:21:46,723
if you have people looking
over your shoulder?

872
01:21:46,807 --> 01:21:50,724
You know who gave Hitler
his power? The clerks
and the bookkeepers.

873
01:21:50,848 --> 01:21:52,391
The civil servants.

874
01:21:53,307 --> 01:21:55,391
I have this one weakness.

875
01:21:55,891 --> 01:21:57,724
I believe in a just God.

876
01:21:58,724 --> 01:22:01,474
I always seem to err
on the side of democracy.

877
01:22:08,016 --> 01:22:10,891
This must be a nice place
to raise a family.

878
01:22:10,975 --> 01:22:12,808
I never made the time.

879
01:22:13,808 --> 01:22:15,725
I'll be dead
in less than a year.

880
01:22:18,642 --> 01:22:20,308
I love this country.

881
01:22:20,809 --> 01:22:23,600
We all do, sir. We all do.

882
01:22:33,309 --> 01:22:37,184
No matter what anyone
tells you, there'll be
no one you can really trust.

883
01:22:41,143 --> 01:22:45,226
I'm afraid
when all is said and done,
we're all just clerks, too.

884
01:23:05,310 --> 01:23:09,018
I was under the impression
that Dr. Ibanez
supported a democracy.

885
01:23:09,144 --> 01:23:11,394
I'm afraid
he's changed his mind.

886
01:23:11,477 --> 01:23:13,894
The doctor's started
to believe
his own propaganda.

887
01:23:13,978 --> 01:23:16,769
I mean, you dreamed
this guy up, Edward,
helped get him elected.

888
01:23:16,811 --> 01:23:18,144
Those are the Soviets.

889
01:23:18,227 --> 01:23:20,227
International Department
of Central Committee members

890
01:23:20,310 --> 01:23:22,894
Trubnikov, Kushelnikov,

891
01:23:22,978 --> 01:23:25,894
who have become
overly interested
in their natural resources,

892
01:23:25,978 --> 01:23:27,395
particularly coffee.

893
01:23:29,145 --> 01:23:32,061
Our economic interests
are being compromised,

894
01:23:32,437 --> 01:23:36,478
to say nothing of the dangers
of a Soviet presence
so close to home.

895
01:23:37,894 --> 01:23:41,895
For security, Edward,
we must establish
our own presence there.

896
01:23:42,478 --> 01:23:44,395
Wait, stop. Can you go back?

897
01:23:45,311 --> 01:23:47,229
Go back a little bit.

898
01:23:50,812 --> 01:23:52,562
Run it from there.

899
01:24:07,146 --> 01:24:08,896
I just thought
I saw something.

900
01:24:08,980 --> 01:24:11,479
I want you two
to put your heads together
on this.

901
01:24:11,646 --> 01:24:14,980
Michael will be
going down there
as an agricultural specialist

902
01:24:15,063 --> 01:24:17,980
with the Mayan Coffee Company.
Non-official.

903
01:24:19,147 --> 01:24:21,063
He'll be our eyes and ears.

904
01:24:21,230 --> 01:24:23,230
Congratulations.
Thank you, sir.

905
01:24:23,564 --> 01:24:24,980
Good luck.
Thank you.

906
01:24:25,980 --> 01:24:28,230
I wouldn't wear
my class ring down there.

907
01:24:28,397 --> 01:24:29,564
Yes, sir. Of course.

908
01:24:29,647 --> 01:24:33,731
I want all intelligence
on this sent directly to me
and no one else.

909
01:24:37,480 --> 01:24:39,605
<i>I believe that's
what you're looking for.</i>

910
01:24:41,981 --> 01:24:43,480
That'll do it.

911
01:25:36,482 --> 01:25:40,649
Mr. Wilson?
This came for you through
the Carlson cover address.

912
01:25:41,899 --> 01:25:43,608
There was no card.

913
01:26:35,776 --> 01:26:38,860
There's been
a potential compromise
down south.

914
01:26:38,985 --> 01:26:40,319
Ulysses.

915
01:26:41,319 --> 01:26:43,068
We can't wait
another 24 hours.

916
01:26:43,152 --> 01:26:46,902
If you can guarantee that
all assets are in place and
prepared to move on my order,

917
01:26:46,986 --> 01:26:49,152
I'm prepared to move as well.

918
01:26:53,444 --> 01:26:55,069
Come back to bed.

919
01:26:56,028 --> 01:26:57,736
What were you talking about?

920
01:26:57,986 --> 01:26:59,694
It's grown-up talk.

921
01:27:00,777 --> 01:27:02,486
I had a nightmare.

922
01:27:02,986 --> 01:27:04,570
Everything's fine.

923
01:27:07,528 --> 01:27:09,570
Could you stay with me
another minute?

924
01:27:14,153 --> 01:27:15,403
Try to get some sleep.

925
01:27:18,486 --> 01:27:19,737
Yes?

926
01:27:21,070 --> 01:27:24,570
We haven't got time to be sure
on this. This whole thing
hinges on support.

927
01:27:24,820 --> 01:27:27,778
If we don't have the support,
I can't guarantee the outcome.

928
01:27:27,820 --> 01:27:29,820
Can you guarantee
the support?

929
01:27:30,987 --> 01:27:33,904
That's not a guarantee.
That's not an answer.

930
01:27:35,237 --> 01:27:39,070
Do what you have to do.
These men aren't ideological.

931
01:27:39,279 --> 01:27:42,237
Put more in their
Christmas stockings,
and they'll fall into place.

932
01:27:42,321 --> 01:27:45,905
Call the station chief.
Get him out of bed.

933
01:27:46,321 --> 01:27:48,613
Margaret tells us that
you work with the CIA.

934
01:27:51,654 --> 01:27:53,988
My wife has
a vivid imagination.

935
01:27:54,363 --> 01:27:57,030
I'm a trade advisor.
A civil servant.

936
01:28:07,071 --> 01:28:08,572
Good night.
Good night.

937
01:28:16,489 --> 01:28:17,780
How dare you speak
to me that way?

938
01:28:17,822 --> 01:28:19,448
You are never to tell anybody
what I do.

939
01:28:19,572 --> 01:28:22,031
How dare you?
Those people are my friends!
I don't have a lot of friends!

940
01:28:22,156 --> 01:28:25,239
You are never to tell anyone
what it is I do. Never.
Do you understand me?

941
01:28:25,323 --> 01:28:27,490
What you do? What you do?
I don't know what you do!

942
01:28:27,573 --> 01:28:29,989
You leave at five,
you're home at ten,
seven days a week.

943
01:28:30,072 --> 01:28:31,406
You don't say
a damn word to me!

944
01:28:31,490 --> 01:28:34,406
I live with a ghost!
I don't know what you do!

945
01:28:42,324 --> 01:28:43,656
Call back.

946
01:28:50,907 --> 01:28:53,407
They're ready.
Launch the operation.

947
01:28:54,657 --> 01:28:56,073
Say something.

948
01:28:56,407 --> 01:28:58,324
Say something.
I have to go now.

949
01:28:58,449 --> 01:29:01,240
Say something! Talk to me!
Say something!

950
01:29:01,324 --> 01:29:03,407
Look at me. Say something.

951
01:29:31,408 --> 01:29:34,909
Remember what I said.
Don't touch anything.
All right?

952
01:29:38,242 --> 01:29:40,992
Merry Christmas,
Margaret. Edward.
Merry Christmas.

953
01:29:41,117 --> 01:29:42,742
Is this young Edward?

954
01:29:42,784 --> 01:29:46,409
Would you like to come inside
and meet our very
special guest this evening?

955
01:29:50,743 --> 01:29:52,409
Santa Claus.

956
01:29:52,618 --> 01:29:54,326
- Would you like
to meet Santa?
- Yeah.

957
01:29:54,409 --> 01:29:55,576
Come along.

958
01:29:56,077 --> 01:29:58,659
Toddy is wonderful
with children.
Yes, she is.

959
01:29:58,743 --> 01:30:00,576
Come and meet Santa.

960
01:30:02,826 --> 01:30:05,743
Would you like a drink,
Edward?
Thank you.

961
01:30:07,202 --> 01:30:09,910
I believe
congratulations are in order.

962
01:30:10,868 --> 01:30:14,410
The doctor has
no more patients
because of malpractice.

963
01:30:17,327 --> 01:30:19,077
Gentlemen.
Edward.

964
01:30:22,911 --> 01:30:24,161
Phillip.

965
01:30:24,369 --> 01:30:25,494
Bill.

966
01:30:25,952 --> 01:30:27,244
Gentlemen,

967
01:30:27,994 --> 01:30:31,161
you can all be very proud
of what you've started.

968
01:30:34,660 --> 01:30:35,744
Merry Christmas.

969
01:30:35,827 --> 01:30:37,952
- Merry Christmas, Bill.
- Merry Christmas.

970
01:30:47,661 --> 01:30:49,661
Christmas
is full of surprises.

971
01:30:50,162 --> 01:30:52,162
Do you like surprises
under the tree?

972
01:30:53,578 --> 01:30:57,495
Well, we'll make sure
you have lots of surprises

973
01:30:57,995 --> 01:30:59,828
and things like that. Okay?

974
01:30:59,995 --> 01:31:02,745
I'm sure Mom and Dad
agree that
that would be a good idea.

975
01:31:02,828 --> 01:31:05,828
Surprises are the best part
of Christmas, don't you think?

976
01:31:05,912 --> 01:31:08,995
How about games?

977
01:31:10,829 --> 01:31:13,162
How about ball games?

978
01:31:16,829 --> 01:31:18,829
- Can I get you a towel?
- I'm so sorry.

979
01:31:18,913 --> 01:31:20,829
Are you all right?

980
01:31:20,913 --> 01:31:22,246
All right. It's all right.

981
01:31:22,330 --> 01:31:23,913
Can you take me
home, please?

982
01:31:23,996 --> 01:31:25,663
I think we should go home.
Lower your voice.

983
01:31:25,746 --> 01:31:28,413
You can use our bath
if you'd like.
I might have some dry clothes.

984
01:31:28,497 --> 01:31:31,580
Thank you.
Come with me, Edward.
It's all right. Come with me.

985
01:31:31,747 --> 01:31:33,747
Can I help you up,
Mrs. Wilson?

986
01:32:34,999 --> 01:32:36,916
Did you know that
Phillip is going to be

987
01:32:36,999 --> 01:32:39,582
on the Mayan Coffee Company's
board of directors?

988
01:32:42,416 --> 01:32:45,166
Remember what I said to you
about friends.

989
01:32:57,833 --> 01:32:59,333
<i>You look good, Edward.</i>

990
01:33:00,250 --> 01:33:02,1000
How long has it been?
Seven, eight years?

991
01:33:03,917 --> 01:33:06,084
A lot of water
under the bridge.

992
01:33:08,667 --> 01:33:11,501
Carolyn and I,
we just bought
our first house.

993
01:33:12,167 --> 01:33:15,501
And everything's already
broken. I spend my weekends
fixing things.

994
01:33:15,750 --> 01:33:20,167
By the time I get everything
fixed, it'll be time
to sell the fucking house.

995
01:33:21,751 --> 01:33:24,668
Maybe you can give me
a heads-up on somebody.

996
01:33:29,918 --> 01:33:33,335
You're asking me
to give you FBI files
on an American citizen?

997
01:33:33,417 --> 01:33:36,751
You know I can't do that.
It's against the law
to spy on citizens.

998
01:33:38,168 --> 01:33:39,502
Keep it.

999
01:33:39,751 --> 01:33:41,918
Maybe someday
you'll change your mind.

1000
01:34:09,836 --> 01:34:11,336
May I come in?

1001
01:34:25,503 --> 01:34:27,920
You know, I've never
been in your office.

1002
01:34:29,087 --> 01:34:30,670
How was the fishing?

1003
01:34:31,753 --> 01:34:34,587
It was a bad year.
The water is too high.

1004
01:34:36,337 --> 01:34:37,671
I understand you wanted to

1005
01:34:37,754 --> 01:34:41,170
personally give me
the Operation Zapata list
yourself.

1006
01:34:45,337 --> 01:34:47,088
There isn't one, is there?

1007
01:34:51,337 --> 01:34:53,088
You know it was
a silent operation.

1008
01:34:53,171 --> 01:34:55,171
It wasn't silent enough.

1009
01:34:59,921 --> 01:35:04,338
I've been asked by
the President to suggest
who we no longer need with us.

1010
01:35:07,922 --> 01:35:10,005
Who would you recommend,
Edward?

1011
01:35:10,088 --> 01:35:12,255
I serve at the pleasure
of the Director, sir.

1012
01:35:14,089 --> 01:35:16,005
I'm just a gatekeeper.

1013
01:35:17,422 --> 01:35:20,588
And why is it that
people like us
choose to serve,

1014
01:35:21,423 --> 01:35:24,506
for nickels a day,
in a profession that makes us

1015
01:35:25,005 --> 01:35:28,339
constantly
look over our shoulder
to see who's watching us?

1016
01:35:29,005 --> 01:35:30,839
When will you
make your decision?

1017
01:35:33,840 --> 01:35:35,089
Decision?

1018
01:35:38,756 --> 01:35:42,756
I serve at the discretion
of the President
of the United States.

1019
01:35:43,923 --> 01:35:47,090
I will do what I think
is best for the country.

1020
01:35:53,507 --> 01:35:57,173
It's important that
we find out who's responsible.

1021
01:36:00,757 --> 01:36:02,757
Good night.
Good night.

1022
01:36:15,590 --> 01:36:19,924
<i>At 2242, call received
on Berlin base chief's
operational line.</i>

1023
01:36:20,091 --> 01:36:23,924
Man says he's senior officer,
KGB. Would not give name.

1024
01:36:24,675 --> 01:36:26,341
Open up. Thanks.

1025
01:36:31,925 --> 01:36:34,925
"KGB officer asks when
Mr. Edward Wilson is coming.

1026
01:36:35,009 --> 01:36:37,842
"He wants to know
Mr. Edward Wilson's response."

1027
01:36:38,259 --> 01:36:40,425
Tell him
Mr. Edward Wilson is here,

1028
01:36:40,758 --> 01:36:44,009
and would like to know
what he intends to
provide us with in return.

1029
01:36:50,175 --> 01:36:52,592
He says,
"In return for safe journey,

1030
01:36:52,676 --> 01:36:55,592
"he will provide Mr. Wilson
with clear understanding

1031
01:36:55,676 --> 01:36:58,676
"of last three losses
in Moscow

1032
01:36:59,093 --> 01:37:02,509
"and identities of
Soviet agents in your country,

1033
01:37:03,676 --> 01:37:06,260
"penetrations
of Moscow station.

1034
01:37:07,343 --> 01:37:10,592
"He will also speak personally
with Mr. Edward Wilson about

1035
01:37:12,176 --> 01:37:13,510
"Ulysses.

1036
01:37:14,343 --> 01:37:16,760
"Things only he knows
of Ulysses,

1037
01:37:16,843 --> 01:37:19,427
"how he thinks,
what he plans to do,

1038
01:37:20,010 --> 01:37:24,011
"and what he wants
Mr. Edward Wilson to think
he is doing.

1039
01:37:25,094 --> 01:37:28,593
"To establish bonafides,
he will carry with him

1040
01:37:28,677 --> 01:37:33,677
"KGB surveillance photographs
of all CIA officers in Moscow

1041
01:37:35,510 --> 01:37:40,261
"and would be more than happy
to take polygraph."

1042
01:37:49,428 --> 01:37:50,678
Ulysses.

1043
01:37:55,178 --> 01:37:57,428
Ask him what his weakness is.

1044
01:38:11,512 --> 01:38:12,928
"The cold."

1045
01:38:15,178 --> 01:38:16,846
Let's get him over here.

1046
01:38:17,596 --> 01:38:21,179
My name is
Valentin Gregorievich Mironov.

1047
01:38:21,762 --> 01:38:25,263
My children's names are
Anatoly and Sergei.

1048
01:38:25,263 --> 01:38:29,762
My father played the cello.
I play the violin.
But you know this.

1049
01:38:30,013 --> 01:38:34,179
I risk my life to come all
the way to tell you this, to
confirm what you already know.

1050
01:38:34,263 --> 01:38:36,096
You failed the polygraph,
Mr. Mironov.

1051
01:38:36,096 --> 01:38:38,430
You know every Russian
fails polygraph.

1052
01:38:39,680 --> 01:38:42,513
Your polygraph
doesn't understand
the Russian soul.

1053
01:38:47,180 --> 01:38:51,847
What more do you want?
I've given you my bonafides,
the names of agents,

1054
01:38:52,264 --> 01:38:55,680
<i>who has been compromised,
who you need to know about.</i>

1055
01:38:56,597 --> 01:38:59,180
<i>I want to speak to
Mr. Edward Wilson.</i>

1056
01:39:00,180 --> 01:39:02,681
We were told
Mironov was with these men
the day the photo was taken.

1057
01:39:02,764 --> 01:39:04,180
<i>Your immediate superior?</i>

1058
01:39:04,264 --> 01:39:06,180
We're not even sure that
any of the circled men
are him.

1059
01:39:06,264 --> 01:39:09,180
<i>I told you this
three times already.
Sergei Budanov.</i>

1060
01:39:09,514 --> 01:39:11,931
<i>I want to speak to
Mr. Edward Wilson.</i>

1061
01:39:16,681 --> 01:39:18,348
I would like some tea.

1062
01:39:22,182 --> 01:39:23,432
There isn't any.

1063
01:39:23,515 --> 01:39:25,681
I get thirsty
when I say too much.

1064
01:39:25,931 --> 01:39:28,848
You going to keep up
this inane questioning
for much longer?

1065
01:39:30,182 --> 01:39:33,599
There's nothing you've told us
we don't know, Mr. Mironov.

1066
01:39:34,849 --> 01:39:36,932
I think you better try
a little harder.

1067
01:39:37,016 --> 01:39:40,765
I didn't come here
to deal with children,
Mr. Edison.

1068
01:39:41,348 --> 01:39:43,016
Or is it Mr. Brocco?

1069
01:39:45,515 --> 01:39:47,433
We do our homework, too.

1070
01:39:57,516 --> 01:40:00,099
Hello, Mr. Mironov.
I'm Mr. Wilson.

1071
01:40:05,600 --> 01:40:07,100
Hello, Mother.

1072
01:40:10,100 --> 01:40:15,100
Ulysses is obsessed with you.
Night and day,
you are always on his mind.

1073
01:40:16,184 --> 01:40:17,766
He trusts nobody.

1074
01:40:17,933 --> 01:40:21,684
The only one
whom he lets close
is his aide, Sasha.

1075
01:40:22,517 --> 01:40:25,851
He is methodical,
he plans things
years in advance.

1076
01:40:26,767 --> 01:40:29,601
For instance, you should know
he has developed a friendship

1077
01:40:29,684 --> 01:40:31,767
with a certain
neighbor of yours.

1078
01:40:32,101 --> 01:40:36,101
Fidel Castro. A young man
he has high hopes for.

1079
01:40:36,684 --> 01:40:40,435
I understand you had
a most interesting
fish swim your way.

1080
01:40:40,851 --> 01:40:44,435
Mr. Allen thought
it might be possible
for me to speak with him.

1081
01:40:44,518 --> 01:40:46,851
With you as the chaperone,
of course.

1082
01:40:46,934 --> 01:40:49,185
I brought him a little gift
I'm sure he'll appreciate.

1083
01:40:49,268 --> 01:40:51,435
Send Mironov in immediately.

1084
01:40:52,185 --> 01:40:54,518
It'll be nice
to be closely working
with you again.

1085
01:40:54,852 --> 01:40:59,102
I expect you to show me
Washington. We can
paint the town red together.

1086
01:41:01,102 --> 01:41:03,518
Valentin Mironov,
Arch Cummings.

1087
01:41:03,685 --> 01:41:06,602
It is a great pleasure
to meet you.
My pleasure.

1088
01:41:06,685 --> 01:41:07,685
Now, please sit down.

1089
01:41:07,769 --> 01:41:11,102
It's nice to have someone
like you on our side
of the street.

1090
01:41:12,519 --> 01:41:14,436
I thought you may enjoy this.

1091
01:41:14,686 --> 01:41:17,519
It's something
you might appreciate.
I hope you haven't read it.

1092
01:41:19,269 --> 01:41:20,686
Very clever.

1093
01:41:22,186 --> 01:41:23,603
Thank you.

1094
01:41:26,853 --> 01:41:28,936
All Russia is our orchard.

1095
01:41:29,352 --> 01:41:31,770
The land is great
and beautiful.

1096
01:41:32,103 --> 01:41:34,853
There are many
wonderful places in it.

1097
01:41:34,936 --> 01:41:36,603
Think, Anya.

1098
01:41:36,770 --> 01:41:39,187
Your grandfather,
your great-grandfather...

1099
01:41:39,270 --> 01:41:43,520
This is a very bad
translation. It is
much funnier in Russian.

1100
01:41:46,353 --> 01:41:48,021
And now,
doesn't something human
look at you

1101
01:41:48,103 --> 01:41:50,270
from every cherry
in the orchard?

1102
01:41:50,687 --> 01:41:52,937
From every leaf
and every stalk?

1103
01:41:53,854 --> 01:41:56,188
Don't you hear their voices?

1104
01:41:57,188 --> 01:42:00,604
It's awful.
Your orchard is terrible!

1105
01:42:00,937 --> 01:42:03,687
And when in the evening
or at night, when you walk
through the orchard

1106
01:42:03,771 --> 01:42:06,104
and the old bark glows
with the dim light

1107
01:42:06,188 --> 01:42:09,188
and the old cherry trees seem
to be dreaming of all that was

1108
01:42:09,271 --> 01:42:12,104
a hundred, two hundred
years ago, and are repressed
by their heavy visions.

1109
01:42:12,104 --> 01:42:13,772
I'm due at a meeting.

1110
01:42:14,104 --> 01:42:17,521
We've left those 200 years
behind us, but so far,
we gained nothing at all.

1111
01:42:17,772 --> 01:42:20,355
We don't yet know
what the past is to be to us.

1112
01:42:21,022 --> 01:42:26,272
We only philosophize.
We complain that we are dull,
or we drink vodka.

1113
01:42:27,105 --> 01:42:30,189
For it's so clear
that in order to
begin to live in the present,

1114
01:42:30,272 --> 01:42:32,105
we must first redeem the past.

1115
01:42:37,689 --> 01:42:39,189
Are you Laura?

1116
01:42:39,939 --> 01:42:41,105
What?

1117
01:42:41,189 --> 01:42:44,356
Are you Laura? I'm supposed to
offer you a ride.

1118
01:43:08,024 --> 01:43:09,607
Hello, Edward.

1119
01:43:10,857 --> 01:43:12,107
Hello, Laura.

1120
01:43:13,857 --> 01:43:15,690
Why all the mystery?

1121
01:43:19,107 --> 01:43:20,941
Do you have children?

1122
01:43:21,107 --> 01:43:22,774
I have a boy.

1123
01:43:23,774 --> 01:43:25,608
Edward Junior.

1124
01:43:30,274 --> 01:43:31,942
Do you have anybody?

1125
01:43:35,775 --> 01:43:37,191
A cat.

1126
01:43:42,108 --> 01:43:45,775
I've often imagined
what my life would have
been like with you.

1127
01:43:47,359 --> 01:43:49,359
And what did you imagine?

1128
01:43:50,609 --> 01:43:52,692
I thought you might teach.

1129
01:43:53,275 --> 01:43:54,942
Probably poetry.

1130
01:43:56,859 --> 01:43:59,609
I saw us living
in a small college town.

1131
01:44:14,859 --> 01:44:19,610
You once said to me you were
afraid your life was
already planned out for you.

1132
01:44:23,777 --> 01:44:25,944
Are you doing
what you want to do?

1133
01:44:28,610 --> 01:44:30,860
My life has been
full of surprises.

1134
01:44:57,111 --> 01:44:59,195
You owe me
a day at the beach.

1135
01:45:43,196 --> 01:45:45,029
How long do you think
you'll be?

1136
01:45:45,613 --> 01:45:47,446
As long as it takes.

1137
01:45:52,030 --> 01:45:54,780
I think maybe
I'll go ahead.
All right.

1138
01:45:59,030 --> 01:46:02,197
<i>Nothing else
is built the same</i>

1139
01:46:02,364 --> 01:46:05,947
<i>Nothing in the world</i>

1140
01:46:06,030 --> 01:46:08,947
<i>As the soft
and wavy frame...</i>

1141
01:46:10,280 --> 01:46:11,531
Mother?

1142
01:46:13,948 --> 01:46:16,197
There was an envelope for you
on the desk.

1143
01:46:18,115 --> 01:46:19,447
You look lovely.

1144
01:46:19,614 --> 01:46:21,447
Thank you, darling.

1145
01:47:09,449 --> 01:47:11,699
It's not enough
that you ignore me
our whole life?

1146
01:47:11,783 --> 01:47:13,366
You have to humiliate me?
Margaret, please.

1147
01:47:13,449 --> 01:47:15,117
You disgust me!
Calm down, darling.

1148
01:47:15,533 --> 01:47:16,699
You're disgusting!

1149
01:47:42,534 --> 01:47:44,034
We'll start from the last.

1150
01:47:46,867 --> 01:47:48,784
<i>So suppose
the dame ain't right</i>

1151
01:47:48,867 --> 01:47:50,618
<i>Or completely
free from flaws</i>

1152
01:48:16,952 --> 01:48:18,952
Mother forgot
some of her things.

1153
01:48:31,452 --> 01:48:33,120
I'll see you at home.

1154
01:49:32,705 --> 01:49:34,205
Are you Laura?

1155
01:49:35,289 --> 01:49:36,539
Yes.

1156
01:49:36,622 --> 01:49:38,789
I was asked to give you this.

1157
01:49:52,039 --> 01:49:55,123
<i>In an
unprecedented effort to
improve U.S.-Soviet ties,</i>

1158
01:49:55,123 --> 01:49:58,540
<i>Premier Khrushchev
began his 10-day tour
of the United States today.</i>

1159
01:49:58,622 --> 01:50:01,290
<i>The visit
will start with a tour
by President Eisenhower</i>

1160
01:50:01,373 --> 01:50:02,623
<i>of our nation's capital,</i>

1161
01:50:02,706 --> 01:50:05,540
<i>followed by
a highly anticipated speech
at the United Nations.</i>

1162
01:50:05,623 --> 01:50:07,290
All right,
now set it down.

1163
01:50:07,373 --> 01:50:10,623
<i>Following that,
the Soviet Premier
will travel across the country</i>

1164
01:50:10,707 --> 01:50:12,040
<i>to more casual destinations,</i>

1165
01:50:12,123 --> 01:50:16,124
<i>including America's mighty
steel mills, wheat farms,
and, yes, Disneyland.</i>

1166
01:50:16,957 --> 01:50:19,790
<i>President Eisenhower greeted
Mr. Khrushchev this morning</i>

1167
01:50:19,874 --> 01:50:22,124
<i>at Andrews Air Force Base,
as they prepare to discuss...</i>

1168
01:50:22,207 --> 01:50:23,457
It's perfect.

1169
01:50:23,457 --> 01:50:25,957
<i>...the ever-threatening
military build-up by the Reds.</i>

1170
01:50:26,040 --> 01:50:28,957
Our glee club's
been chosen to compete
in a national competition.

1171
01:50:29,040 --> 01:50:30,957
<i>Now, back to
The Classical Hour.</i>

1172
01:50:31,040 --> 01:50:32,874
Would you come with me?

1173
01:50:33,708 --> 01:50:35,374
Would you like me to?

1174
01:50:36,040 --> 01:50:37,624
